<br>
And we do this why exactly?  Because everyone else does it?  Because its the norm in our society?  As if that justifies it.  Teaching a system of morality or ethics to children is more than just telling them something is right or wrong . . . it's showing them, by our actions.  Children need to see that the rules apply - not just to them, but to everyone, including their parents.  Otherwise, its just a punishment system for when they are caught - which just teaches them to be better liars.<br>
<br>
The really bad effect of lying to them in this way, though, is the violation of trust.  Children seem to have complete trust in their parents growing up.  But this doesn't last forever . . . it goes away.  Perhaps it has something to do with them realizing the hypocrisy in their parents, who tell them lying is wrong on one hand, and then tell them about Santa Claus on the other.  &quot;Lying is wrong, don't do it, if you do, Santa will know and you won't get presents from him&quot;.  Talk about hypocrisy.<br>
<br>
You don't have to lie to children to show them the wondrous nature of the world.  The world we live in is incredible enough in its own right, without the need to make something up to make it moreso. <p></br>

