<br>
Considering this from a purely ideological standpoint, I would concede that lying to children about the existence of Santa Claus is wrong, as lying in general is wrong and should not be done in a perfect world.  However, this is not a perfect world, and lying (or perhaps, simply not telling the whole truth) is not always bad.  There are times that lying is for the greater good - when you need to get that annoying person out of your office or off the phone so you can get that shipment of food off to a third world country.  Or to keep your girlfriend thinking that it's life as usual so you can surprise her with a proposal.  There are tons of reasons to tell &quot;white lies&quot; (or to creatively leave out information such that someone infers what you want them to), as I'm sure everyone has at some point had to do - do you think of yourself as a bad person for that?  If not, then you should understand my point.  Perpetuating a belief in Santa Claus is not wrong in the real world.  You are not telling your children the whole truth, and are mixing it with some non-truth; but it serves to offer a belief in the unknown, unknowable, and unatainable.  As the child gets to the point where it understands that there is no Santa Claus, he/she is also coming ready to understand that not *all* un-truth is bad.  The trick is, if you teach kids that lying is not always bad when they are young and impressionable, you are setting them up poorly for adulthood.  If you teach kids that everyone is always telling the truth while they are young and impressionable, you are setting them up poorly for adulthood as well.  Santa Claus, aside from being what I consider a tool for harmless magic and fun, is also an important lesson for adult life.<br>
<br>
Besides, I don't want to have to explain to a 2 year old that Mickey Mouse is actually just a guy in a suit, clowns aren't all fun and games - they will eat you if you go to sleep, and the easter bunny didn't deserve to get his ass kicked by Jay and Silent Bob.<br>
<br>
I agree with you in an ideal world scrooge, but but I'd say you hold no water in the real one.  what do you say?<br>
