Baekin  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666699><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub79.ezboard.com/udelarawyldheart.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Delara Wyldheart</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://delarawyldheart.freeservers.com/images/starblink.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Membership Coordinator</span><br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(5/24/02 4:26:32 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub79.ezboard.com/finfinitusvindicatfrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=18.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://delarawyldheart.freeservers.com/images/yinyang.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Santa Claus: Man, Myth, Lie...</span><hr size=1> Looking into the reason I told my children about Santa, I remember not being able to wait for Alex's first Christmas and at 11 months old he was sitting in Santa's lap screaming like a banshee so I could get a picture. When he finally made the connection between Santa and getting gifts it became fun for me. I looked forward to Christmas morning much like I did when I was a kid. As the years progressed we made the connection between getting gifts and the spirit of giving. <br>
<br>
Understand that only one present under the tree was ever from Santa and it has always been the one thing they really really wanted.<br>
<br>
Once Alex was old enought to know the real truth of Santa he too still looked forward to Chrismas morning so he could see the look on Eryn's face when she saw the present she got for him. This transition has taken place for Eryn as well.<br>
<br>
<br>
It's not about the lie, it is about the spirit of giving and the wanting to enstill the idea of giving unconditionally of ones self just to make someone else feel good inside.<br>
<br>
So I don't think its such a bad thing for parents to tell their children about Santa. Alex and Eryn still get one present from Santa every year and they always will. <br>
