          Today I have a 10 year old son and a 7 year old daughter and yes they still do believe in Santa Claus. I do believe that this year I will have to sit my son down as my father did to me and tell the &quot;truth&quot; about Santa and explain the spirit of Saint Nicholas. Do I think that my parents perpetuated a lie or that I myself am perpetuating a lie? I do not. I am carrying down a &quot;Tradition&quot; that has been in my, and many others, family for many generations and would hope that the world does not get so analytical to the point where we as parents are being questioned about whether or not our choice to carry on a tradition ,based on fact or fiction, could or would do unending harm to our children. I woke up on December 25th for many years after being told the &quot;truth&quot; at the same time and did the same thing and had the same smile as I did before. I thank my parents for carrying on a tradition to us so that we may enjoy carrying on this tradition to our children and hope that they will be able to carry it on to their children. At least the government hasn't taken Christmas from us.......YET!!!<br>
<br>
I am not refuting the fact that lies can harm our children and can even scar them for life. I am however refuting the fact that allowing our children to believe in the good of mankind and instilling the spirit of giving into our children can in any way be a bad thing. Have you seen the news lately? I don't allow my children to watch the news yet because they are too young to have to experience the &quot;truth&quot; of how terrible  mankind can really be. I , as I sit here typing this, am thinking about going Christmas shopping tommorow because doing that also puts a big smile on my face. I may just have too many presents *AGAIN* this year to fit under the tree and have to line the walls with them. Why? A childs smile can say a million words my friends. And when that makes you smile too? PRICELESS!!! <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub79.ezboard.com/uknobbie69p.showPublicProfile?language=EN>KNOBBIE69P</A> at: 5/24/02 11:30:39 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666699><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub79.ezboard.com/umorkenlar.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Morkenlar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Councilman</span><br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(5/29/02 6:53:09 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub79.ezboard.com/finfinitusvindicatfrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=18.topic&index=14>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Santa Claus: Man, Myth, Lie...</span><hr size=1> ok. . . . so what we have as defenses of telling Children about Santa are:<br>
<br>
1.  It makes them wonder at the world.<br>
<br>
My response here is simple - there's plenty of wonder to the world, both natural and manufactured, that people take for granted.  You could do a better job by showing them the wonders that people ignore.  Caterpillars turning to butterflies is a truly wonderous thing - far more impressive than Santa Claus - and incidentally is quite true.<br>
<br>
2.  It instills a &quot;giving spirit&quot; in them.<br>
<br>
My response - you can do this without lying to them.  Tell them the story of St Nick . . . but don't lie and tell them about the imaginary guy at the north pole.  If you can accomplish the same thing with truth and lies, why lie?<br>
<br>
3.  It makes them happy.<br>
<br>
My response - immaterial.  Drugs would also make them happy, but you don't give them drugs, do you?<br>
<br>
4.  It's a tradition.<br>
<br>
Tradition = not always right.<br>
<br>
5.  There was a St. Nick that gave presents to children.<br>
<br>
Doesn't justify lying to them, about a guy at the North Pole . . . tell them the real story.<br>
<br>
6.  Children need to learn early that they are not always told the truth, so they can think about what they are told critically to form their own opinions.<br>
<br>
This would be the only reason I would agree with - except that it doesn't seem to work, and then parents complain about their children not listening/trusting them completely like they used to.  (hello!  they caught you lying to them!  duh.) <p></br>

